I'm here as I am today because I got lucky and ran into the right people I could open up to. Life is... hard. No amount of hard work could pull me anywhere. I felt broken and lost. Now I feel bitter for being lied to about my conditions, about who I am, and how hard it was.

Those failures made me an angry person too. I was disconnected with people and even myself. No money, few friends, living off of left overs from a restaurant gig. I was a powdered keg and didn't understand why I hated my own body either.

I couldn't get better alone.

I didn't understand anything. My parents failed to equip me with the necessary tools to sort myself out. I was even kicked from home because my father thought I was gay. It's hard to accept the reason why all those things I tried that failed weren't my fault.

A little over a decade ago, I watched my confidence in myself get chipped away from many numerous failures for projects I wanted to do. I couldn't keep them going because I didnt understand what depression was, nor did I know I had adhd. Stopping for breaks was treated as failure

The idea and ability of weaponizing my adhd is new. These last 2 years with therapy has gotten me to this control and it's a far cry still from perfect, but it use to be worse. So much so. I didn't even know I had it, people told me I couldn't, that I was just scatterbrained.

Sometimes you run into realizations that recontextualizes traumatic events in your past. Sometimes you even find more forgiveness for yourself, but that can be difficult to accept when you spent years in self loathing and regret. That's part of my struggle as of late.
